s in the intentional structure or in the attentional state of the discourse.
    The differential use of these linguistic markers provides one piece of evidence for considering these two components to be distinct.
    Because these linguistic devices function explicitly as indicators of discourse structure, it becomes clear that they are best seen as providing information at the discourse level, and not at the sentence level; hence, certain kinds of questions (e.g., about their contribution to the truth conditions of an individual sentence) do not make sense.
    For example, in the utterance Incidentally, Jane swims every day, the incidentally indicates an interruption of the main flow of discourse rather than affecting in any way the meaning of Jane swims every day.
    Jane's swimming every day could hardly be fortuitous.
    Just as linguistic devices affect structure, so the discourse segmentation affects the interpretation of linguistic expressions in a discourse.
